# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: empower-aircraft-power-adapter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Tracing its origins back to the 1910s, Air France was formed on 30 August 1933 through the merger of five existing airlines in France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] During the Cold War, from 1950 until 1990, it was one of the three main Allied scheduled airlines operating in Germany at West Berlin's Tempelhof and Tegel airports.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1990, it acquired the operations of French domestic carrier Air Inter and international rival UTA – Union de Transports Aériens.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It merged with KLM to form Air France–KLM in 2003.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2018, Air France and its regional subsidiary Hop carried 51.4 million passengers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France operates a mixed fleet of Airbus and Boeing wide-body jets on long-haul routes, and uses Airbus A320 family narrow-body aircraft on short-haul routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France introduced the Airbus A380 on 20 November 2009 with service from Paris to New York.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France Hop (formerly HOP!) operates the majority of its regional domestic and European scheduled services with a fleet of regional jet aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The predecessor companies of Air France date back to Compagnie générale transaérienne (CGT), established in 1909, which flew the world's first scheduled passenger-carrying fixed-wing flights within France in 1913.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] SGTA was the first commercial passenger airline company in France; founded as Lignes Aériennes Farman in 1919, it began a weekly service between Paris and Brussels on 22 March 1919, the world's first international commercial aviation service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Société des lignes Latécoère began airmail services in 1924.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] These airlines built extensive networks across Europe, to French colonies in North Africa and farther afield prior to their merger into Air France in 1933.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1936, Air France added French-built twin engine Potez 62 aircraft to its fleet featuring a two-compartment cabin that could accommodate 14 to 16 passengers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] A high-wing monoplane, it had a wooden fuselage with composite coating while the wings were fabric-covered with a metal leading edge.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Equipped with Hispano-Suiza V-engines, they were used on routes in Europe, South America and the Far East.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Although cruising at only 280 km/h (175 mph), the Potez 62 was a robust and reliable workhorse for Air France and remained in service until the Second World War with one used by the Free French Air Force.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] During World War II, Air France moved its operations to Casablanca, Morocco.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 26 June 1945, all of France's air transport companies were nationalised.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 29 December 1945, a decree of the French Government granted Air France the management of the entire French air transport network.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France recruited its first female flight attendants in 1946.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The same year the airline opened its first air terminal at Les Invalides in central Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It was linked to Paris Le Bourget Airport, Air France's first operations and engineering base, by coach.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] At that time the network covered 160,000 km, claimed to be the longest in the world.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Société Nationale Air France was set up on 1 January 1946.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] European schedules were initially operated by a fleet of Douglas DC-3 aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 1 July 1946, Air France started direct flights between Paris and New York via refuelling stops at Shannon and Gander.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Douglas DC-4 piston-engine airliners covered the route in just under 20 hours.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In September 1947, Air France's network stretched east from New York, Fort de France and Buenos Aires to Shanghai.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] By 1948, Air France operated 130 aircraft, one of the largest fleets in the world.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Between 1947 and 1965, the airline operated Lockheed Constellations on passenger and cargo services worldwide.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1946 and 1948, respectively, the French government authorised the creation of two private airlines: Transports Aériens Internationaux – later Transports Aériens Intercontinentaux – (TAI) and SATI.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1949, the latter became part of Union Aéromaritime de Transport (UAT), a private French international airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 4 August 1948, Max Hymans was appointed the president.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] During his 13-year tenure he would implement modernisation practices centred on the introduction of jet aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1949, the company became a co-founder of Société Internationale de Télécommunications Aéronautiques (SITA), an airline telecommunications services company.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1952, Air France moved its operations and engineering base to the new Orly Airport South terminal.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France entered the jet age in August 1953, flying the original, short-lived de Havilland Comet series 1A Paris-Rome-Beirut.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In the mid 1950s, it also operated the Vickers Viscount turboprop, with twelve entering service between May 1953 and August 1954 on the European routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 26 September 1953, the government instructed Air France to share long-distance routes with new private airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This was followed by the Ministry of Public Works and Transport's imposition of an accord on Air France, Aigle Azur, TAI and UAT, under which some routes to Africa, Asia and the Pacific region were transferred to private carriers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 23 February 1960, the Ministry of Public Works and Transport transferred Air France's domestic monopoly to Air Inter.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] To compensate for the loss of its domestic network Air France was given a stake in Air Inter.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The following day Air France was instructed to share African routes with Air Afrique and UAT.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline started uninterrupted jet operations in 1960 with the Sud Aviation Caravelle and the Boeing 707; jet airliners cut travel times in half and improved comfort.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France later became an early Boeing 747 operator and eventually had one of the world's largest Boeing 747 fleets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 1 February 1963, the government formalised division of routes between Air France and its private sector rivals.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] These routes were allocated to the new Union de Transports Aériens (UTA), a new private airline resulting from the merger of TAI and UAT.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] UTA also got exclusive rights between Japan, New Caledonia and New Zealand, South Africa and Réunion island in the Indian Ocean, as well as Los Angeles and Tahiti.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1974, Air France began shifting the bulk of operations to the new Charles de Gaulle Airport north of Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] By the early 1980s, only Corsica, Martinique, Guadeloupe, most services to French Guiana, Réunion, the Maghreb region, Eastern Europe (except the USSR), Southern Europe (except Greece and Italy), and one daily service to New York (JFK) remained at Orly.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1974, Air France also became the world's first operator of the Airbus A300 twin-engine widebody plane, Airbus Industrie's first commercial airliner for which it was a launch customer.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 21 January 1976, Air France operated its inaugural supersonic transport (SST) service on the Paris (Charles de Gaulle) to Rio (via Dakar) route with Anglo-French BAC-Aérospatiale Concorde F-BVFA.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Supersonic services from Paris (CDG) to Washington Dulles International Airport began on 24 May 1976, also with F-BVFA.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Service to New York (JFK) – the only remaining Concorde service until its end – commenced on 22 November 1977.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Paris to New York was flown in 3 hours 23 minutes, at about twice the speed of sound.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Approval for flights to the United States was initially withheld due to noise protests.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Eventually, services to Mexico City via Washington, D.C., were started.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France became one of only two airlines – British Airways being the other – to regularly operate supersonic services, and continued daily transatlantic Concorde service until late May 2003.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] By 1983, Air France's golden jubilee, the workforce numbered more than 34,000, its fleet about 100 jet aircraft (including 33 Boeing 747s) and its 634,400 km network served 150 destinations in 73 countries.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This made Air France the fourth-largest scheduled passenger airline in the world, as well as the second-largest scheduled freight carrier.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France also codeshared with regional French airlines, TAT being the most prominent.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] TAT would later operate several regional international routes on behalf of Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1983, Air France began passenger flights to South Korea, being the first European airline to do so.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1986, the government relaxed its policy of dividing traffic rights for scheduled services between Air France, Air Inter and UTA, without route overlaps between them.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The decision opened some of Air France's most lucrative routes on which it had enjoyed a government-sanctioned monopoly since 1963 and which were within its exclusive sphere of influence, to rival airlines, notably UTA.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The changes enabled UTA to launch scheduled services to new destinations within Air France's sphere, in competition with that airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Paris-San Francisco became the first route UTA served in competition with Air France non-stop from Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France responded by extending some non-stop Paris-Los Angeles services to Papeete, Tahiti, which competed with UTA on Los Angeles-Papeete.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] UTA's ability to secure traffic rights outside its traditional sphere in competition with Air France was the result of a campaign to lobby the government to enable it to grow faster, becoming more dynamic and more profitable.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1987, Air France together with Lufthansa, Iberia and SAS founded Amadeus, an IT company (also known as a GDS) that would enable travel agencies to sell the founders and other airlines' products from a single system.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1988, Air France was a launch customer for the fly-by-wire (FBW) Airbus A320 narrow-body twin, along with Air Inter and British Caledonian.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It became the first airline to take delivery of the A320 in March 1988, and along with Air Inter, became the first airlines to introduce A320 service on short-haul routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 12 January 1990, the operations of government-owned Air France, semi-public Air Inter and wholly private Union de Transports Aériens (UTA) were merged into an enlarged Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France's acquisition of UTA and Air Inter was part of an early 1990s government plan to create a unified, national air carrier with the economies of scale and global reach to counter potential threats from the liberalisation of the European Union's internal air transport market.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 25 July 1994, a new holding company, Groupe Air France, was set up by decree.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Groupe Air France became operational on 1 September 1994.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It acquired the Air France group's majority shareholdings in Air France and Air Inter (subsequently renamed Air Inter Europe).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 31 August 1994, Stephen Wolf, a former United Airlines CEO, was appointed adviser to the Air France group's chairman Christian Blanc.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Wolf was credited with the introduction of Air France's hub and spoke operation at Paris Charles de Gaulle.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Wolf resigned in 1996 to take over as CEO at US Airways.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1997, Air Inter Europe was absorbed into Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 19 February 1999, French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin's Plural Left government approved Air France's partial privatisation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Its shares were listed on the Paris stock exchange on 22 February 1999.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In June 1999, Air France and Delta Air Lines formed a bilateral transatlantic partnership.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 22 June 2000, this expanded into the SkyTeam global airline alliance.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 30 September 2003, Air France and Netherlands-based KLM Royal Dutch Airlines announced the merger of the two airlines, with the new company to be known as Air France–KLM.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] At that point former Air France shareholders owned 81% of the new firm (44% owned by the French state, 37% by private shareholders), former KLM shareholders the rest.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The decision of the Jean-Pierre Raffarin government to reduce the French state's shareholding in the former Air France group from 54.4% to 44% of the newly created Air France–KLM Group effectively privatised the new airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In December 2004, the state sold 18.4% of its equity in Air France–KLM.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The state's shareholding in Air France–KLM subsequently fell to just under 20%.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France–KLM became the largest airline in the world in terms of operating revenues, and third-largest (largest in Europe) in passenger kilometres.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Although owned by a single company, Air France and KLM continued to fly under their own brand names.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As of March 2004, the group employed 71,654 people.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As of March 2007, the group employed 102,422 personnel.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 17 October 2007, the creation of a profit and revenue-sharing transatlantic joint venture between Air France-KLM and Delta Air Lines was announced during a press conference at Air France-KLM's headquarters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The venture became effective on 29 March 2008.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It aimed to exploit transatlantic opportunities to capture a major share of long-haul business traffic from London Heathrow, which opened to unrestricted competition on that day as a result of the "Open Skies" pact between the EU and US.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It was envisaged that Air France and Delta would begin nine daily round trips between London-Heathrow and destinations in the US, including a daily London (Heathrow) to Los Angeles service by Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Once the new Air France-Delta venture received antitrust immunity, it was to be extended to the other two transatlantic SkyTeam partners, enabling all four partners to codeshare flights as well as to share revenue and profit.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The new transatlantic joint venture marks the Air France-KLM Group's second major expansion in the London market, following the launch of CityJet-operated short-haul services from London City Airport that have been aimed at business travellers in the City's financial services industry.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] However, the daily London (Heathrow) to Los Angeles service was not as successful as hoped, and was discontinued in November 2008.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 12 January 2012, Air France-KLM announced a three-year transformation plan, called Transform 2015, to restore profitability.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The plan was to restore competitiveness through cost-cutting, restructuring the short- and medium-haul operations and rapidly reducing debt.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The main objective of this plan was to turn Air France-KLM back into a world player by 2015.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France had been losing 700 million euros a year.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As the financial results of 2011 demonstrated, the long-haul operations, also subject to increasing competition, would not be able to offset these losses.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 22 February 2012, Air France released its plan for the summer schedule.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Because of the uncertain economic environment, Air France-KLM set a limit of 1.4% maximum increase in capacity from 25 March 2012 to 28 October 2012.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 21 June 2012, Air France-KLM had announced its decision to cut just under 10% of the total 53,000 workforce (about 5,000 jobs) by the end of 2013 in an attempt to restore profitability.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline expected to lose 1,700 jobs through natural turnover and the rest by voluntary redundancies.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As of August 2012, the Transform 2015 plan was accepted by ground staff and pilot unions but rejected by cabin crew unions.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] At the beginning of July 2012, it was announced that Air France-KLM found partners for the new African start-up airline Air France, which was co-founded by six countries in Central Africa to replace the former Air Afrique.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] But several problems and two partners, who decided to back out, delayed the implementation of the project.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Following its launch, Air France announced it would commence operations in 2013.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In September 2013, Air France introduced a brand new Economy product along with an improved Premium Economy seat and service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It is expected that the new improvements would be fitted on aircraft from June 2014 onwards.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In October 2013, Air France-KLM announced it was writing off the 25% stake in Alitalia, as it was hesitant the struggling carrier would obtain the 300 million euros in financing.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The group has denied Alitalia of additional funds as it is currently struggling to restructure itself to profitability with the Transform 2015 plan.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In December 2013, Air France announced that Cityjet no longer meets the short haul needs of the group and is in the process of closing a deal with German firm Intro Aviation by the end of Q1 of 2014.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2014, the airline was targeted by a negative publicity campaign, spearheaded by PETA, for being the only major airline that permits the transport of primates for research.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2022, the airline announced it would stop transporting nonhuman primates.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 4 February 2014, the new business product was unveiled, featuring a fully flat bed from Zodiac Aerospace.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The seat was fitted on Boeing 777 aircraft from June 2014 onwards.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In September 2014, Air France announced it would sell a 3 per cent stake in travel technology company Amadeus IT Group for $438 million.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Late in 2015, Air France faced a financial crisis, which was exacerbated by a pilot's strike against the airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline answered the strike by announcing it would cut some 2,900 jobs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In December 2015, Air France announced the retirement of its last Boeing 747-400 with a special scenic flight on 14 January 2016.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline operated the 747 in several variants since 1970.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In January 2017, Air France received its first Boeing 787–9.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In November, CityJet no longer operated on Air France flights and the affected destinations were served by Air France and HOP! from then on.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In July 2017, Air France-KLM entered into a multi-airline strategic partnership with Delta Air Lines, China Eastern Airlines and Virgin Atlantic, solidifying the existing ties between the carriers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Under the agreement Delta and China Eastern would each buy 10% of Air France-KLM, while Air France-KLM would buy 31% of Virgin Atlantic.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In December 2019, the purchase of Virgin Atlantic was cancelled.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France announced it would terminate services to Iran from September 2018, explaining the concern that the route to Iran is no longer commercially viable due to the redefined US sanctions.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In December 2018, Anne Rigail was appointed as Executive Director of the company.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France's head office is located in the Roissypôle complex on the grounds of Charles de Gaulle Airport and in the commune of Tremblay-en-France, Seine-Saint-Denis, near the city of Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The French firm Groupement d'Etudes et de Méthodes d'Ordonnancement (GEMO) managed the project.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The architect was Valode & Pistre and the design consultants were Sechaud-Boyssut and Trouvin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The project cost 137,000,000 euros (less than 700 million francs).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The runways of the airport are visible from the building.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The Air France Operations Control Centre (*OCC*, French: Centre de Contrôle des Opérations, *CCO*), which coordinates Air France flights worldwide, is situated at the AF head office.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] For about 30 years prior to December 1995, Air France's headquarters were located in a tower adjacent to the Gare Montparnasse rail station in the Montparnasse area and the 15th arrondissement of Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] By 1991, two bids for the purchase of the Square Max Hymans building had been made.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] By 1992, the complex was sold to Mutuelle générale de l'Éducation nationale (MGEN) for 1.6 billion francs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] By that year, Air France had planned to move its head office to Roissypôle, taking 50,000 square metres (540,000 sq ft) of space inside the hotel, office, and shopping complex on the grounds of Charles de Gaulle Airport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] After Air France moved to Tremblay-en-France, the ownership of the former head office complex was transferred.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On a previous occasion, the head office was at *2 rue marbeuf* in the 8th arrondissement of Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France's United States offices are in the 125 West 55th Street building in Midtown Manhattan, New York City.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France first signed a lease to occupy the building in 1991.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The site also formerly housed the New York City ticket office for Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France-KLM's head office for the United Kingdom and Ireland operations, which includes facilities for Air France and KLM, is located in Plesman House in Hatton Cross.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The facility's inauguration was on 6 July 2006.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France moved the office from Hounslow to Hatton.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France Cité PN, located at Charles de Gaulle Airport, acts as the airline's crew base.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The building, developed by Valode & Pistre, opened in February 2006.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The first phase consisted of 33,400 square metres (360,000 sq ft) of space and 4,300 parking spaces.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The building is connected to the Air France head office.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Until 2022, Air France operated the Air France Vaccinations Center in the 7th arrondissement of Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The centre distributed vaccines for international travel.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Since 2001, the centre was the only French vaccination centre certified International Organization for Standardization (ISO) 9001.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2005, the centre moved from the Aérogare des Invalides to its current location.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In late 2022, Air France sold its vaccination centre to Elsan.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The Aérogare des Invalides in the 7th arrondissement of Paris houses the Agence Air France Invalides and the Air France Museum.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Until 2005, the building hosted the Air France Vaccinations Centre.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 28 August 1959, Air France opened a ticket and information agency in the former air terminal in Invalides, targeting transit passengers and customers from offices and companies in the Invalides area.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France and Dutch affiliate Transavia formed Transavia France, a low-cost joint venture in May 2007, based at Orly Airport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air Corsica and Air France Hop all operate flights on behalf of Air France, either as subsidiaries or as franchisees.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As of January 2019, Air France was investigating how it could shut down its low-cost subsidiary Joon and absorb its employees and aircraft into the parent company.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Owing to the disputed status of Taiwan, Air France could not operate flights to the island under its own name.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 1993, its subsidiary, Air Charter, began operating flights between Paris and Taipei via Hong Kong, but after Air Charter ceased operations in 1998, a subsidiary called **Air France Asie** was established.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline was one of a number of airline subsidiaries flying under the "Asia" name with the purpose of flying to Taiwan, which included Japan Asia Airways (a Japan Airlines subsidiary), KLM Asia, British Asia Airways, Swissair Asia, and Australia Asia Airlines (a Qantas subsidiary).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The livery of Air France Asie differed from that of Air France by having blue and white stripes on the tailfin, rather than blue, white and red ones, representing the French Tricolour.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France Asie used two Airbus A340-200 aircraft, F-GLZD and F-GLZE, and two Boeing 747-428Ms, F-GISA and F-GISC.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Similarly, **Air France Cargo Asie** used a 747–200 Combi (for passengers and freight), F-GCBH) or the all-cargo (F-GCBL, F-GPAN and F-GBOX).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France Asie ceased operations in 2004 while Air France Cargo Asie ceased operations in 2007.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2010, Air France migrated from an internally managed passenger service system (Alpha3) that manages reservation, inventory and pricing to an external system (Altéa) managed by Amadeus.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In rail ventures, Air France and Veolia are looking into jointly operating high-speed rail services in Europe.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Routes have become available to operators in accordance with European rail liberalisation on 1 January 2010.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France's present livery is a "Eurowhite" scheme, comprising a white fuselage with the blue Air France title and design.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The tail is white with a series of parallel red and blue lines across the tail at an angle, and a small European flag at the top.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The engines have the old Air France (and formerly Air Orient) logo painted on, though only on newer aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This livery has been in use since the late 1970s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Prior to the "Eurowhite" livery, Air France aircraft had a bare-metal underside, extending up to a blue cheat-line that ran across the cabin windows.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Above the cheat-line the fuselage was again white, with Air France titles and a French flag.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The tail was white with two thick blue lines, which tapered from the rear of the tail and met at a point towards the front bottom.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This basic livery, with minor variations, would appear on all post-war Air France aircraft until the late 1970s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In January 2009, to coincide with Air France's new logo, a new livery was unveiled.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France rolled out its new livery on 11 February 2009.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The 2009 livery saw the tail slightly changed; there are now three blue bars running down instead of the previous four.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The bars also now curve at the bottom, reflecting the design of the logo.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2017, Air France received their first Boeing 787 with a revised livery which included larger Air France titles.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2019, Air France revised the livery with the arrival of the Airbus A350, with blue winglets featuring the *hippocampe ailé*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This coincided with reintroducing the practice of naming each of their aircraft, with the name written under the front cabin windows; the first A350-900 was named after the city of Toulouse.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2021, Air France once again revised the livery, while most elements were still identical to the 2019 version, the *hippocampe ailé* icon is now added between cockpit windows and front cabin doors, replacing the SkyTeam logo.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The aircraft type, SkyTeam logo and Air France-KLM logo now feature at the back of the fuselage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In the 1950s and 1960s, graphic designer Jean Carlu produced promotional posters for Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The new official song played before and after Air France flights (during boarding and after landing) is 'The World Can Be Yours' by Telepopmusik.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France has used different popular music groups for its marketing and on-board ambience, ranging from The Chemical Brothers in 1999 to Telepopmusik in 2010.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France launched a new ad campaign in 2015 designed by BETC and directed by We Are From LA, focusing on French culture.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Along with the ad campaign and print ads, Air France also introduced a similarly themed safety video.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The music is a customised version of Glass Candy's song *Warm in the Winter*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France uniforms denote the ranks for the flight attendants.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Two silver sleeve stripes denote a senior Purser.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] One silver sleeve stripe denote a Purser.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Flight attendants do not have any sleeve stripes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The female cabin crew uniforms feature the stripes on the breast pocket rather than the sleeve for their male counterparts.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France's current uniforms were created by French fashion designer Christian Lacroix.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Upon its formation, Air France adopted the seahorse logo of its predecessor Air Orient, known as the *hippocampe ailé* (sometimes derisively called "la crevette" – or shrimp – by its employees), as its insignia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Prior to the Air France-KLM merger, the *hippocampe ailé* was used on the nose section of aircraft next to the Groupe Air France title; after the merger, the Air France-KLM logo was substituted at the nose area, and the *hippocampe ailé* was relocated to engine nacelles.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The acronym "AF" has also featured prominently on the airline's flag and its signage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 7 January 2009, Air France officially changed its logo to a red stripe.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As of 2022, Air France flies to 29 domestic destinations and 201 international destinations in 94 countries (including overseas departments and territories of France) across six continents, including 19 in the United States and 16 in Italy.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This includes Air France Cargo services and destinations served by franchisees Air Corsica, and Air France HOP.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Most of Air France's international flights operate from Paris-Charles de Gaulle.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France also has a strong presence at the following French airports: Lyon-Saint-Exupéry, Marseille Provence, Toulouse Blagnac and Nice Côte d'Azur.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 16 September 2011, Air France-KLM announced orders for 50 Airbus A350s and Boeing 787s with 60 options, to be operated by both Air France and KLM.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France-KLM committed 37 Boeing 787s, 25 directly and 12 leased, of which 16 are earmarked for Air France to replace some A340-300s, subsequent A340s would be replaced by Airbus A350s from 2019.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The first Boeing 787-9 entered into service with KLM in 2015 and with Air France in early 2017.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France-KLM had 28 A350s on firm order.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In June 2019, the group announced a revision of the original order with Air France becoming the sole operator of the Airbus A350, with KLM only operating Boeing 787s, including six originally earmarked for Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The first Airbus A350-900 *(named Toulouse*) was delivered to Air France on 27 September 2019.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In September 2023 Air France-KLM announced an order for 50 Airbus A350 900 and A350 1000 with combined options for 40 more with deliveries scheduled for 2026, which will be allocated to both Air France and KLM to replace their aging Airbus A330 and Boeing 777 200ER aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In August 2025 the Group converted eight of the 11 -1000 orders to the -900 variant for better flexibility across the group.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France operates a fleet of all four variants of the Airbus A320 family aircraft with a total of 114 jets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In July 2019, a first order was announced as part of replacing its narrow-body fleet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The smaller Airbus A318 and A319 fleet will be replaced by 60 Airbus A220-300s starting in 2021.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France would have to cut emission by half by 2024 for flights within mainland France as part of conditions of a €7 billion state support from France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] As a result, Air France plans to place more Airbus A220 aircraft onto its domestic network.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The five Air France Concordes were retired on 31 May 2003, as a result of insufficient demand following the 25 July 2000 crash of AF Concorde F-BTSC, at Gonesse (near Charles de Gaulle Airport), as well as higher fuel and maintenance costs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] British Airways flew its last Concorde service on 24 October 2003.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Concorde F-BVFA was transferred to the Steven F.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Udvar-Hazy Center at Washington Dulles International Airport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] F-BVFB was given to the Sinsheim Auto & Technik Museum in Germany, F-BTSD to the Musée de l'Air et de l'Espace at Le Bourget Airport in Paris, while F-BVFC returned to its place of manufacture in Toulouse, at the Airbus factory.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] F-BVFF is the only example to remain at Charles de Gaulle Airport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline started operating the Boeing 747 on 3 June 1970, when a 747-100 was put into service that was delivered on 20 March that year.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It would go on to operate the -200, -300 and -400 variants.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In January 2016, Air France finally retired its last Boeing 747-400.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] They were replaced by Airbus A380 and Boeing 777-300ER aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Freighter versions were replaced by Boeing 777Fs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France offers a mix of three and four cabin configurations for international long haul routes, featuring La Première (select aircraft), Business, Premium Economy and Economy.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Personal screens with audio video on demand is available in all cabins on all long-haul aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] European short-haul and medium-haul flights feature a three cabin configuration with Business, Premium Economy, and Economy.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] La Première is Air France's long-haul first class product.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] It is available on selected Boeing 777-300ERs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The Première cabin features wood and leather seats which recline 180°, forming two-metre long beds.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Each seat features a 10.4" touchscreen personal screen with interactive gaming and audio video on demand, a privacy divider, automassage feature, reading light, storage drawer, noise-cancelling headphones, personal telephone, and laptop power ports.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Each passenger is also provided with a personalised coat service, pure merino wool blanket, a "boudoir-style" cushion, and a travel kit featuring Biologique Recherche facial and body care products to moisturise and refresh the skin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Turndown service includes a mattress, a duvet, hypoallergenic feather pillow, sleepwear, a dust bag for shoes, and a pair of slippers À la carte on-demand meal services feature entrées created by Chef Guy Martin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Private lounge access is offered worldwide featuring a chauffeured car to the aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] La Première is not available on Airbus A330s, A350s, and most Boeing 777s, on which Business is the highest cabin class.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Four-class 777-300ER configurations are equipped with four seats.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France is also planning to introduce an updated version of La Première in 2025, with the Airbus A350-900 being a potential aircraft to be equipped with the updated cabin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The new La Première experience has been introduced in March 2025 and will equip the Boeing 777-300ER.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The new private suite offers five windows and occupies 3.5 square metres (38 sq ft).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The seat can be transformed into a 2-metre-long (7 ft) bed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The first flight with the new cabin flew from Paris to New York JFK on 8 April 2025.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Business, Air France's long-haul business class product, is available on all long haul aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Business features angled lie-flat seats which recline to two metres in length.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Each seat includes a 10.4" touchscreen TV monitor with interactive gaming and AVOD, reading light, personal telephone, and laptop power ports.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Meal service features three-course meals and a cheese service, or an express menu served shortly after takeoff.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The current business class product features Zodiac Aerospace Cirrus seats is designed by Mark Collins of Design Investment, specialised in the world of high-end transportation and by the design and branding agency, Brandimage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Initially debuting on Boeing 777s in June 2014, they were retrofitted onto all other aircraft types except for the Boeing 747-400, Airbus A380s, and Airbus A340-300 as they were to be retired from the fleet by 2016, 2019, and 2020 respectively.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] A total of 2,102 seats would be installed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The new cabin features a 1-2-1 layout as opposed to a 2-3-2 layout previously used on 777s or the 2-2-2 seat configuration of the Airbus A330s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The new 16-inch (41 cm) screen offers a unique onboard navigation experience similar to a tablet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] With a completely redesigned user interface and available in 12 languages (French, English, Spanish, Brazilian Portuguese, Chinese, Japanese, Korean, German, Italian, Dutch, Russian and Arabic), choosing an entertainment program from over 1,000 hours of entertainment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Premium Economy is featured on all long-haul flights.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This cabin made its debut on Boeing 777s and Airbus A330s beginning in late 2009 and early 2010.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The seats were also installed on Airbus A340-300s between late 2009 and early 2010 and the Airbus A380s in late 2010 and early 2011.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Passengers receive double baggage allowance, priority airport services, lounge access (for a fee), and extra frequent flier mileage.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] A new improved Premium Economy seat using the same shell was introduced from June 2014 on the Boeing 777 aircraft, featuring better cushioning and improved foot rest, adding comfort to the passenger.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France's economy class long-haul product features seats that recline up to 118°.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The current long-haul Economy seat, which debuted on the Boeing 777-300ER, includes winged headrests, a personal telephone, and a touchscreen TV monitor with AVOD Interactive Entertainment System which have been installed on all of Air France's long-haul fleet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On long-haul flights, a menu is presented with a choice of two meals.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Short- and medium-haul Economy services are operated by Airbus A320 family aircraft with different seating arrangements.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France is one of the few airlines who features winged headrests on short-to-medium-haul aircraft in both classes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On short-haul flights, a snack is served, while on medium-haul flights, a three-course cold meal is served.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Free alcoholic beverages are available on all flights, including champagne.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On most aircraft, Air France offers extra-legroom seats in economy called Seat Plus.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] These seats are located in the economy-class exit rows and other rows depending on the aircraft type, offering at least 4 inches (10 cm) more seat pitch (36 inches [91 cm] versus the usual 32 inches [81 cm] in standard economy seats).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Seat Plus prices vary by flight time, but it is free to elites and passengers with a full-fare economy ticket.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The seats would be installed along with the new La Première, Business, and Premium Economy seats from June 2014 till summer 2016 on the Boeing 777 aircraft, the core of the fleet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] All other aircraft would be retrofitted except the Airbus A340-300s, Airbus A380-800s, and Boeing 747-400s, as all three types would be retired by 2020.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] For La Première, Air France's first class menu is designed by Guy Martin, chef of Le Grand Vefour, a Michelin three-star restaurant in Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Menu items include hors d'oeuvres, entrées, bread basket, and cheeses, along with a dessert cart including pastries, petit fours, and tartlets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On long-haul flights, Air France also serves complimentary champagne and wine to passengers in all classes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France offers Audio Video on Demand (AVOD) in all cabins on all long haul aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The in flight entertainment system features multiple channels of video, audio, music, and games.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] *Air France Magazine*, the airline's in-flight publication, is included at each seat, and *Air France Madame*, a fashion luxury magazine with a feminine perspective, is included in La Première and Business cabins and lounges.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On all flights, all films may be watched in English, Spanish, and French.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Selected films on all flights are also available in Chinese, Japanese, Hindi, and Korean.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline offers Berlitz International language courses via the in-flight entertainment system.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 29 May 2013, KLM and Air France launched a pilot to test inflight Wi-Fi.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Both airlines have equipped one Boeing 777-300ER of each of their fleets with Wi-Fi.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Using the inflight Wi-Fi, passengers can stay online using their Wi-Fi enabled smartphones, laptops, or tablets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Wireless service would commence once the flight has reached 20,000 feet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France lounges are known as Le Salon, and are open to La Première and Business passengers, as well as Flying Blue Gold, Flying Blue Platinum and SkyTeam Elite Plus members.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Worldwide, there are 530 Air France and SkyTeam lounges in 300 international airports on every continent except Antarctica.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Flying Blue, the frequent flyer program of Air France-KLM, awards members points based on distance travelled and class of service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The program is divided into standard (Explorer), Elite (Silver) and Elite Plus (Gold and Platinum) statuses.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Explorer is the basic level which is attained upon entry into the program.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Elite status is attained by accruing a certain number of XP (Experience Points) within one year.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Elite Silver, Elite Plus Gold, and Elite Plus Platinum cards have added benefits.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] An invitation-only card called Club 2000 is attributed to some VIPs, celebrities and politicians.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Officially, it provides the same benefits as Platinum status but numerous sources confirm it almost guarantees upgrade to Business or La Première.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Flying Blue succeeded Air France's previous frequent flyer program, Fréquence Plus, which operated until the Air France-KLM merger in 2003.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 14 November 2008, Air France released the first picture of an Airbus A320 that had been repainted in the full 1946 paint scheme to celebrate the airline's 75th anniversary.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This heritage aircraft was planned to fly under the special colours until early 2010.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] In 2013 the aircraft was withdrawn from use for scrapping.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] On 24 June 2024, Air France was voted for multiple top awards by Skytrax; *2024* *World's Best First Class Catering*, *Best Airline in Western Europe* and *Best First Class Lounge Dining*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Air France has been involved in a number of major accidents and incidents.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The airline's deadliest accident occurred on 1 June 2009, when Air France Flight 447, an Airbus A330-203, crashed into the Atlantic Ocean killing all 228 on board.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] Another notable crash in Air France's records occurred on 25 July 2000, when Air France Flight 4590, a Concorde, caught fire immediately after take-off due to metal debris on the runway damaging a tire, which produced debris that struck a fuel tank on the underside of the wing, catching fire.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] The fire started to disintegrate the aircraft's left wing and the plane started to tilt to its side.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] This caused the aircraft to crash into a hotel on the outskirts of Gonesse, France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-france] All 109 passengers and crew inside Flight 4590, as well as four people inside the hotel, were killed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Tata, Tata himself flew its first single-engine de Havilland Puss Moth, carrying air mail from Karachi to Bombay's Juhu aerodrome and later continuing to Madras (currently Chennai).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After World War II, it was nationalised by the Government of India in 1953 and renamed to *Air India*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 21 February 1960, it took delivery of its first Boeing 707 named *Gauri Shankar* and became the first Asian airline to induct a jet aircraft in its fleet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2000 to 2001, attempts were made to privatise Air India, and from 2006 onwards it suffered losses following its merger with Indian Airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Another privatisation attempt was launched in 2017, culminating in the return of ownership of the airline and associated properties to the Tata Group after 69 years in 2022.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India also operates flights to domestic and Asian destinations through its subsidiary Air India Express.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India operates a mix of narrow body aircraft such as the Airbus A320 family used for most domestic and short-haul international routes and wide body aircraft such as the Airbus A350, Boeing 777, and Boeing 787 aircraft for long haul international routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's mascot is the *Maharajah* ('great king'), and the erstwhile logo consisted of a flying swan with the wheel of Konark inside it, before being replaced by a new logo inspired by the airline's Jharokha window pattern in 2023.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India had its origin in Tata Sons, founded by J.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Tata, an Indian aviator and business tycoon.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In April 1932, Tata won a contract to carry mail for Imperial Airways and the aviation department of Tata Sons was formed with two single-engine de Havilland Puss Moths.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 15 October 1932, Tata flew a Puss Moth carrying air mail from Karachi to Bombay (currently Mumbai) and the aircraft continued to Madras (currently Chennai) piloted by Nevill Vintcent, a former Royal Air Force pilot and friend of Tata.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline fleet consisted of a Puss Moth aircraft and a Leopard Moth.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Initial service included weekly airmail service between Karachi and Madras via Ahmedabad and Bombay.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In its first year of operation, the airline flew 260,000 kilometres (160,000 mi), carrying 155 passengers and 9.72 tonnes (10.71 tons) of mail and made a profit of ₹60,000 (US$630).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Later, the airline launched a domestic flight from Bombay to Trivandrum with a six-seater Miles Merlin.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1938, it was re-christened as *Tata Air Services* and later as *Tata Airlines*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Delhi and Colombo were added to the destinations in 1938.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] During the Second World War, the airline helped the Royal Air Force with troop movements, shipping of supplies, rescue of refugees and maintenance of planes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After World War II, regular commercial service was restored in India and Tata Airlines became a public limited company on 29 July 1946 under the name *Air India*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After the Indian independence in 1947, 49% of the airline was acquired by the Government of India in 1948.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 8 June 1948, a Lockheed Constellation L-749A named *Malabar Princess* (registered *VT-CQP*) took off from Bombay bound for London Heathrow marking the airline's first international flight.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1953, the Government of India passed the Air Corporations Act and purchased a majority stake in the carrier from Tata Sons, though its founder, J.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Tata, would continue as chairman until 1977.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The company was renamed as Air India International Limited and the domestic services were transferred to Indian Airlines as a part of restructuring.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] From 1948 to 1950, the airline introduced services to Nairobi in Africa and to major European destinations Rome, Paris and Düsseldorf.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline took delivery of its first Lockheed Constellation L-1049 named *Rani of Jhansi* (registered *VT-DGL*) and inaugurated services to Bangkok, Hong Kong, Tokyo and Singapore.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 21 February 1960, Air India International inducted its first Boeing 707–420 named *Gauri Shankar* (registered *VT-DJJ*), thereby becoming the first Asian airline to induct a jet aircraft in its fleet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline inaugurated services to New York on 14 May 1960.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 8 June 1962, the airline's name was officially truncated to *Air India* and on 11 June 1962, Air India became the world's first all-jet airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1971, the airline took delivery of its first Boeing 747-200B named *Emperor Ashoka* (registered *VT-EBD*) and introduced a new *Palace in the Sky* livery and branding.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline operated 11 Boeing 747-200 in total.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1986, Air India took delivery of its first Airbus A310-300 and in 1988, the airline took delivery of Boeing 747-300M.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1993, Air India took delivery of a Boeing 747-400 named *Konark* (registered *VT-ESM*) and operated the first non-stop flight between New York and Delhi.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2000–01, attempts were made to re-privatise Air India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2000, Air India introduced services to Shanghai, China.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 23 May 2001, the Ministry of Civil Aviation charged Michael Mascarenhas, the then-managing director, with corruption.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] According to the ministry reports, the airline lost approximately ₹570 million (US$5.9 million) because of extra commissions that Mascarenhas sanctioned, and he was later suspended from the airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In May 2004, Air India launched a wholly owned low cost subsidiary called Air-India Express connecting cities in India with the Middle East and Southeast Asia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Until 2007, Air India mainly operated on international long-haul routes while Indian Airlines operated on domestic and international short-haul routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2007, Air India and Indian Airlines were merged under Air India Limited and the airline took delivery of its first Boeing 777 aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline was invited to be a part of the Star Alliance in 2007.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Around 2006, both Air India and Indian Airlines showed signs of financial crisis as combined losses were ₹7.7 billion (US$80 million).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After the merger of Indian Airlines with Air India in 2007, the losses went up to ₹72 billion (US$750 million) by March 2009.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In July 2009, State Bank of India was appointed to prepare a road map for the recovery of the airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The carrier sold three Airbus A300 and one Boeing 747-300M in March 2009 for $18.75 million to finance the debt.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] By March 2011, Air India had accumulated a debt of ₹426 billion (US$4.4 billion) and an operating loss of ₹220 billion (US$2.3 billion), and was seeking ₹429 billion (US$4.5 billion) from the government.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] A report by the Comptroller and Auditor General blamed the decision to buy 111 new planes and the ill-timed merger with Indian Airlines for the poor financial situation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In August 2011, the invitation to join Star Alliance was suspended as a result of its failure to meet the minimum standards for the membership.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The government pumped ₹32 billion (US$330 million) into Air India in March 2012.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 1 March 2009, Air India made Frankfurt Airport its international hub for onward connections to the United States from India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] However, the airline shut down the Frankfurt hub on 30 October 2010 because of high operating costs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2010, financially less lucrative routes were terminated and the airline planned to open a new hub for its international flights at Dubai.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2012, a study commissioned by the Corporate Affairs Ministry recommended that Air India should be partly privatised.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In May 2012, the carrier invited offers from banks to raise $800 million via external commercial borrowing and bridge financing.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In May 2012, the airline was fined $80,000 by the US Transportation Department for failing to post customer service and tarmac delay contingency plans on its website and adequately inform passengers about its optional fees.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2013, the then-Civil Aviation Minister Ajit Singh stated privatisation was the key to the airline's survival.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] However, the opposition led by the BJP and the CPI(M) slammed the government.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2013, the Indian government planned to delay equity infusion of ₹300 billion (US$3.1 billion) that was slated to be infused into the airline slowly over eight years.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In January 2013, Air India cleared a part of its pending dues through funds raised by selling and leasing back the newly acquired Boeing 787 Dreamliners.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In March 2013, the airline posted its first positive EBITDA after almost six years and 20% growth in its operating revenue since the previous financial year.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India Limited split its engineering and cargo businesses into two separate subsidiaries, Air India Engineering Services Limited (AIESL) and Air India Transport Services Limited (AITSL) in 2013.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In December 2013, the airline appointed veteran pilot SPS Puri as its head of operations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The appointment was criticised by the Air India pilots union as Puri allegedly has multiple violations to his name.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India became the 27th member of Star Alliance on 11 July 2014.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In August 2015, it signed an agreement with Citibank and State Bank of India to raise $300 million in external commercial borrowing to meet working capital requirements.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As of February 2016, Air India was the third largest carrier in India, after IndiGo and Jet Airways with a market share of 15.4%.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 21 May 2021, it was reported that Air India was subjected to a cyberattack where the personal details of about 4.5 million customers around the world were compromised, including passport, credit card details, birthdates, name and ticket information.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's data processor, SITA, reported the data breach to Air India in around February 2021.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The data breach involved all information which was registered in the SITA data processor between 26 August 2011 and 20 February 2021, and the cyberattackers gained access to the systems for a period of 22 days.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India told passengers that there was no conclusive evidence on whether any misuse of the personal data had been reported and urged passengers to immediately change their passwords.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 28 June 2017, the Government of India approved the privatisation of Air India and set up a committee to decide the details.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In March 2018, the Government issued an Expression of Interest (EOI) to sell a 76% stake in Air India, along with low-cost airline Air India Express, and a 50% stake in AISATS, a ground handling joint venture with Singapore Airport Terminal Services (SATS).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] According to the EOI, the new owner would have to take on a debt of ₹333.92 billion (US$3.5 billion) and a bid would have to be submitted by mid-May as the Government wanted to complete the selling process by the end of 2018.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] However, no private firms showed any interest to buy a share in the debt-laden airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Having failed to sell off a majority stake in the airline, the Government decided to completely exit the airline and invited fresh EOIs on 27 January 2020.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In order to attract bidders this time, the government reduced the debt burden on Air India by moving nearly ₹300 billion (US$3.1 billion) of the company's debts and liabilities to a Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In view of the prevailing situation arising out of COVID-19, the last date for submission of interest was extended multiple times and the Government eventually received EOIs from seven parties by December 2020.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Five of these parties were disqualified and the Government invited financial bids for Air India from the two qualified parties in September 2021.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In September 2021, Spice Jet's Ajay Singh-led consortium and Tata Sons submitted their financial bids for Air India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 8 October 2021, Air India along with its low cost carrier Air India Express and fifty per cent of AISATS, a ground handling company, were sold for ₹180 billion (US$1.9 billion) to Tata Group.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 27 January 2022, the airline was officially handed over to Tata Group.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 14 February 2022, after its re-privatisation, the airline appointed İlker Aycı, former chairman of Turkish Airlines as its new CEO and managing director to take charge on or before 1 April 2022 which did not materialise.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In March 2022, Natarajan Chandrasekaran, the chairman of Tata Sons was appointed as the chairman of the airline and in May 2022, Campbell Wilson was announced as the CEO and MD.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After the airline's acquisition, Tata Group began discussions on bringing the other airlines, including Vistara and AirAsia India, where it held a stake, under a unified umbrella.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In November 2022, Air India acquired AirAsia's stake in AirAsia India, renamed it AIX Connect and announced plans to merge it with Air India Express.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 29 November 2022, Air India announced the merger with Vistara by March 2024 with Singapore Airlines which owns a 49% stake in Vistara getting a 25% stake in the newly formed airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Vistara brand would be discontinued post the merger and the brand will operate under the Air India name.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The National Company Law Tribunal approved the merger between Air India and Vistara on 6 June 2024, followed by Singapore Airlines' FDI approval by the Indian government on 30 August 2024.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 12 November 2024, the merger between Vistara and Air India was completed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 15 September 2022, the Tata Group announced Vihaan, a five-year transformation goal aimed at restructuring and transforming Air India in phases.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As part of the plan, Air India announced flights to additional international destinations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The route expansion was supported by improving air-worthiness of existing fleet and leasing aircraft from other airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 14 February 2023, Air India announced an order for 470 aircraft consisting of 250 from Airbus and 220 from Boeing at a cost of US$70 billion, which set the record for the world's largest aircraft order at the time.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 10 August 2023, the airline announced a rebranding exercise named "Vista" with a new livery and logo.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 1 January 2024, Air India announced that it will begin operating its first Airbus A350 aircraft on domestic routes from 22 January 2024 before expanding to international destinations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In July 2024, Air India was reported to be "consolidating its cargo operations" and plans to start a separate entity or a subsidiary like Air India Cargo to handle cargo operations with dedicated freighters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] There has been a 30% increase in the cargo revenues of the Air India Group in FY22-24.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The cargo volume is expected to increase to 2.5 million tonnes by 2027.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India is also developing a "mother software" to handle cargo data and revenue management.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline is streamlining its cargo operations for optimisation of cargo handling.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline has initiated a programme to "onboard, engage and expand with regional, national and global customers".
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In September 2024, Air India announced a $400 million refurbishment programme to modernise 67 of its older aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The programme will commence with the overhaul of 27 narrow-body Airbus A320neo planes, followed by 40 wide-body Boeing aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In October 2025, Air India was reported to be in advanced talks to acquire up to 300 additional aircraft from Airbus and Boeing, including 80–100 widebody models such as the Airbus A350 or Boeing 777X, as part of its fleet renewal and international expansion.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In November 2025, the airline retired its last B737-200, which had been left outside records for more than a decade while being parked in Kolkata after service with India Post.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The plane, that Air India recorded as retired in 2012, was shipped to the firm's office in Bengaluru, where it will be used to train maintenance engineers and flight crew.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India Limited is headquartered in Gurgaon, Haryana, in Sector 16.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Its head office is in 180,000 square feet (17,000 m2) of leased space on the ground floor and floors 1–6 in Block 5 in the Vatika One-on-One complex, and the lease began on 29 September 2023.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India Express, since 2024, occupies space in the same complex.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India moved its headquarters from Air India Building, Mumbai to Delhi in 2013.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The former Mumbai headquarters is a 23-story tower on Marine Drive and was one of the targets of the 1993 Bombay bombings.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It then occupied Indian Airlines House, New Delhi.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2023, Air India moved its headquarters to Gurgaon in the National Capital Region.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India Express began operations on 29 April 2005.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It was initially owned by Air India Charters and mainly operated flights from South India to the Middle East and Southeast Asia in its early days.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In November 2022, Air India acquired AirAsia's stake in AirAsia India, renamed it into AIX Connect and announced plans to merge it with Air India Express.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 1 October 2024, this merger was completed successfully.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India became the first Asian airline to operate freighters when *Air India Cargo* was set up in 1954 and started its freighter operations with a Douglas DC-3 aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India Cargo ended freighter aircraft operations in early 2012.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Alliance Air was a wholly owned subsidiary of Indian Airlines established on 1 April 1996.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It was renamed *Air India Regional* after the merger between Air India and Indian Airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It was renamed back to Alliance Air in 2017 and ceased being a subsidiary of Air India in April 2022 when the Government of India sold Air India to the Tata Group.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's mascot is *the Maharajah* (*high king*).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It was created by Bobby Kooka, the then-commercial director of Air India, and Umesh Rao, an artist with J.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Kooka stated that, "We call him a Maharajah for want of a better description.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] He may look like royalty, but he isn't royal".
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India adopted the Maharajah as its mascot in 1946.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It was used in promoting it although initially designed only for the airline's memo-pads.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The Maharajah was given a makeover in 2015 and the brand is represented by a younger version.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2023, the Maharajah was given a makeover and was revealed that the mascot would only be used in certain aspects of the airline like the premium lounges and crockery.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's colour scheme is red and white.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The aircraft was painted white with red palace-style carvings on the outside of the windows and the airline's name written in red.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The name is written in Hindi on the port side fuselage and in English on the port side tail.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On the starboard side, the name is written in English on the fuselage and in Hindi on the tail.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The window scheme was designed in line with the slogan *Your Palace in the Sky*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The aircraft was earlier named after Indian kings and landmarks.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1989, to supplement its *Flying Palace* livery, Air India introduced a new livery that included a metallic gold spinning wheel on a deep red-coloured tail and a Boeing 747, *Rajendra Chola*, was the first aircraft to be painted in the new colours.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The first logo of Air India was a centaur, a stylised version of Sagittarius shooting an arrow in a circle representing the wheel of Konark.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Tata was introduced in 1948 and represented the airline until 2007.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 22 May 2007, Air India and Indian Airlines unveiled their new livery consisting of a Flying Swan with the wheel of Konark placed inside it.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The flying swan was morphed from the centaur logo, and the chakra was derived from Indian's erstwhile logo.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 15 May 2007, Air India refreshed its livery, making the Rajasthani arches along the windows slightly smaller, extending a stylised line from the tail of the aircraft to the nose and painting the underbelly red.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The new logo features on the tail and the engine covers with red and orange lines running parallel to each other from the front door to the rear door.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After the airline's acquisition by the Tata Group, the airline revealed its brand new logo and livery on 10 August 2023.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The new livery features a palette of deep red, aubergine, and gold with chakra pattern and the new logo is inspired by the airline's Jharokha window pattern.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In December 2023, the airline unveiled new uniforms for its crew and rolled out its new identity with an Airbus A350-900, the first aircraft to be re-branded.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India maintained a collection of Indian art from 1956 comprising works of important Indian artists and photographers, sculptures, wood carvings, glass paintings, rare textiles etc.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The artworks were often sent to be hung in Air India booking offices around the world and used in promotional material.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1967, the company commissioned ashtrays from Salvador Dalí and gifted an elephant calf as payment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2010, a plan to establish a museum from the collection was stalled and the artworks reside in a building in Nariman Point, Mumbai.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India organised the first ever exhibition of these art at the National Gallery of Modern Art in Delhi, titled *Air India Salutes Indian Masters* in 2013.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Following a memorandum of understanding agreed between the airline and the Ministry of Culture, the art collection was transferred to the National Gallery of Modern Art (NGMA) in Mumbai in January 2023.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The art was put up for exhibition titled *Maharaja's Treasure: Select Works of Art from the Famed Air India Collection*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As of November 2025, Air India flies to a total of 87 destinations, including 42 domestic destinations and 45 international destinations in 37 countries across five continents around the world.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Its primary hub is located at Indira Gandhi International Airport, New Delhi, and it has secondary hubs at Kempegowda International Airport, Bengaluru and Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj International Airport, Mumbai.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India operates some of the world's longest non-stop flights.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India is a member of Star Alliance, having become the 27th member of the alliance on 11 July 2014.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As of November 2025, Air India operates a fleet of 189 aircraft, both narrowbody and widebody aircraft with a fleet composed of Airbus A319, A320, A320neo, A321, A321neo, A350 as well as the Boeing 777 and Boeing 787.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1932, Air India started operations with a De Havilland Puss Moth.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 21 February 1960, Air India International inducted its first Boeing 707-420C named *Gauri Shankar* (registered *VT-DJJ*), thereby becoming the first Asian airline to induct a jet aircraft in its fleet.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 1971, the airline took delivery of its first Boeing 747-237B named *Emperor Ashoka* (registered *VT-EBD*) In 1986, Air India took delivery of its first Airbus A310-300.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 4 August 1993, Air India took the delivery of its first Boeing 747-437 named *Konark* (registered *VT-ESM*) In 1989, Indian Airlines introduced the Airbus A320-200 aircraft, which Air India now uses to operate both domestic and international short haul flights.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In 2005, Indian Airlines introduced the smaller A319, which is now used mainly on domestic and regional routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] After the merger in 2007, Air India inducted the A321 to operate mainly on international short-haul routes and leased Airbus A330s to operate on medium-long-haul international routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline's first Boeing 777-200LR aircraft was delivered on 26 July 2007, which was named *Andhra Pradesh*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India received its first Boeing 777-300ER aircraft on 9 October 2007 and the aircraft was named as *Bihar*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India received its first Boeing 787 dreamliner aircraft on 6 September 2012 and commenced flights on 19 September 2012.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India One is the call sign of any Air India aircraft carrying the prime minister, president or the vice-president.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Though the call-sign of Air India is used, these flights are operated on customised Boeing 777-300ER aircraft owned by Indian Air Force and maintained by Air India on a special contract.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As a part of the financial restructuring, Air India sold five of its eight Boeing 777-200LR aircraft to Etihad Airways in December 2013.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] According to the airline, plans for introducing ultra-long flights with service to Seattle, San Francisco and Los Angeles were cancelled due to factors like high fuel prices and weak demand.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In April 2014, the airline decided to sell its remaining three Boeing 777-200LRs as well, citing higher operating costs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 24 April 2014, Air India issued a tender for leasing 14 Airbus A320 aircraft for up to six years, to strengthen its domestic network.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 11 April 2024, Air India sold four of its last remaining Boeing 747-400 jumbo jets US company AerSale.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India is also planning to establish a dedicated subsidiary for cargo operations with dedicated freighters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The 18 Boeing 737s ordered were later transferred to Air India Express.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 14 February 2023, Air India announced an order for 470 aircraft with Airbus and Boeing consisting of 210 A320neo family, 40 A350, 190 737 MAX, 20 787-9, and 10 777-9 aircraft for US$70 billion with deliveries beginning late 2023.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 10 December 2024, an additional order of 100 aircraft with Airbus converting previous options was confirmed consisting of 90 A320neo family aircraft and 10 A350 aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 29 January 2026, an additional order of 30 aircraft out of its 50 options was made for its subsidiary, Air India Express consisting of 20 Boeing 737 MAX 8 and 10 Boeing 737 MAX 10 aircraft and also 15 orders of existing a321neo was converted into Airbus A321XLR.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The Boeing 777-300ERs that have operated with Air India since before its privatisation have a three-class configuration with first, business, and economy class.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] These include the carrier's older, 2-3-2 business class cabins and 3-3-3 economy class cabins.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India also operates ex-Etihad 777-300ERs which feature a different product compared to their legacy 777-300ERs, albeit also in a three-class configuration(First Class, Business Class, and Economy).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's Boeing 787-8 Dreamliners have a similar product to its older 777s but do not have first class, opting for a two-class configuration with a 2-2-2 business class and economy class.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] These aircraft are gradually being retrofitted with new interiors in a three-class configuration(Business class, Premium Economy, and Economy).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's A350-900 aircraft have a three-class configuration with business, premium economy, and economy class.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In November 2024, the merger between Air India and Vistara was completed, and former Vistara aircraft started operating under Air India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The 787-9 Dreamliners which Air India inherited from this merger are configured in a three-class layout.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's took delivery of its first factory-fit 787-9 Dreamliner in January 2026, which is configured in a three-class layout(Business Class, Premium Economy, and Economy).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's widebody fleet is equipped with seatback on-demand in-flight entertainment systems on which passengers can choose from available content.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] This varies from the Thales i5000 on the 777-300ER, the Thales i8000 on the 787-8s, to the Panasonic eX3 on the A350-900 and 787-9.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The legacy 777 and 787 product are being replaced with Thales' Avant Up system.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Thales will also line-fit further deliveries of the A350-900 and the 787-9 with the same system.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India does not offer seatback entertainment on its narrowbody fleet, with the exception of the A321LR, which uses Panasonic's eX1 system.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On its other narrowbodies, and as an interim solution on its legacy widebody fleet, Air India uses the Bluebox streaming IFE service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] *Namaste.ai* is the current in-flight magazine published in English by Air India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] It replaced *Shubh Yatra* (meaning *Happy Journey*), which was a bilingual in-flight magazine published in English and Hindi.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] On 1 January 2025, Air India announced that it rolled out free onboard WiFi on all flights operated by the carrier's A350, Boeing 787-9 and select A321neo aircraft.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Other planes would get Wi-Fi connectivity after they go through a refurbishment.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The carrier became the first airline in the nation to offer such complimentary service within India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In April 2026, Air India selected Hughes Network Systems to transform its in-flight connectivity.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline is also the global launch customer for a common connectivity platform that will be deployed across its widebody fleet, including the Airbus A350-1000, Boeing 787-8, and Boeing 777-300ER.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] For the A350 fleet, Air India will utilise the Airbus HBCplus programme, while the Boeing aircraft will be retrofitted with RAVE Aerospace Ka-band terminals.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Following the merger of Air India and Vistara, Flying Returns and Club Vistara were combined and rebranded as Maharaja Club.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As the flag carrier, Air India is often involved in the evacuation of civilians during wars.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The airline entered the Guinness Book of World Records for the most people evacuated by a civil airliner.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Over 111,000 people were evacuated from Amman to Mumbai, a distance of 4,117 kilometres (2,558 mi), by operating 488 flights from 13 August to 11 October 1990 – lasting 59 days.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The operation was carried out during Persian Gulf War to evacuate Indian expatriates from Kuwait and Iraq.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] The event was later featured in the film *Airlift*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In February–March 2011, Air India evacuated more than 15,000 Indian nationals during the Libyan civil war.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In March–April 2015, the airline was involved in *Operation Raahat* during the Yemeni civil war.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In August 2021, Air India evacuated 669 people under *Operation Devi Shakti* from war-torn Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In February 2022, Air India evacuated Indian citizens from Russia and Ukraine as a part of *Operation Ganga* during the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] In October 2023, the airline evacuated people from Israel during the Gaza war as a part of *Operation Ajay*.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] Air India's ground services became the first ground service provider to acquire ISO 9002 certification on 31 January 2001.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/air-india] As of November 2025, Air India has been involved in eleven fatal crashes and twenty ground fatalities, two of which were caused by acts of terrorism.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] An **airline** is a company that provides a regular service of air transportation for passengers or freight (cargo).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Airlines use aircraft to supply these services.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Many passenger airlines also carry cargo in the belly of their aircraft, while dedicated cargo airlines focus solely on freight transport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Generally, airlines are recognized with an air operating certificate or license issued by a governmental aviation body.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] These airlines may be scheduled or charter operators.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Airline ownership has seen a shift from mostly personal ownership until the 1930s to government-ownership of major airlines from the 1940s to 1980s and back to large-scale privatization following the mid-1980s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Since the 1980s, there has been a trend of major airline mergers and the formation of partnerships or alliances for codeshare agreements, in which they both offer and operate the same flight.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The largest alliances are Star Alliance, SkyTeam and Oneworld.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Airline alliances coordinate their passenger service programs (such as lounges and frequent-flyer programs), offer special interline tickets and often engage in extensive codesharing (sometimes systemwide).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] DELAG, *Deutsche Luftschiffahrts-Aktiengesellschaft*, was the world’s first commercial passenger airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It was founded on November 16, 1909, and began services in June 1910, providing a regular service until 1935.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] DELAG operated airships manufactured by the Zeppelin Company.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Compagnie générale transaérienne (CGT) was founded on October 10, 1909, making it the oldest airline company, which began cargo operations in April 1911 and began regular passenger operations in March 1913—weekly return fixed-wing flights.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] CGT was the first of the companies that would eventually merge to become Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] A fixed-wing scheduled airline was started in the United States in January 1914.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Petersburg–Tampa Airboat Line was piloted by Tony Jannus and flew from St.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The British airship, HM Airship R34 was the first aircraft of any type to carry passengers across the Atlantic Ocean when on 2 July 1919 it left Scotland, travelled to New York and returned.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Aircraft Transport and Travel (AT&T), formed by George Holt Thomas in 1916 as a fixed-wing airline; via a series of takeovers and mergers, this company is the earliest predecessor company of British Airways.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Using a fleet of former military Airco DH.4A biplanes that had been modified to carry two passengers in the fuselage, it operated relief flights between Folkestone and Ghent, Belgium.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] On July 15, 1919, the company flew a proving flight across the English Channel, despite a lack of support from the British government.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] H Shaw in an Airco DH.9 between RAF Hendon and Paris – Le Bourget Airport, the flight took 2 hours and 30 minutes at £21 per passenger.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] On August 25, 1919, the company used DH.16s to pioneer a regular service from Hounslow Heath Aerodrome to Paris's Le Bourget, the first daily international service in the world.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The airline soon gained a reputation for reliability, despite problems with bad weather, and began to attract European competition.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In November 1919, it won the first British civil airmail contract.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Six Royal Air Force Airco DH.9A aircraft were lent to the company, to operate the airmail service between Hawkinge and Cologne.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1920, they were returned to the Royal Air Force.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Other British competitors were quick to follow – Handley Page Transport was established in 1919 and used the company's converted wartime Type O/400 bombers with a capacity for 12 passengers, to run a London-Paris passenger service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Société des lignes Latécoère, a predecessor of Air France, later known as Aéropostale, started its first airmail service in late 1924 to Spain.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Société Générale des Transports Aériens was created in late 1919, by the Farman brothers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It began a weekly service between Paris and Brussels on 22 March 1919, the world's first international commercial aviation service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Farman F.60 Goliath plane flew scheduled services from Toussus-le-Noble to Kenley, near Croydon, England.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Another early French airline was the Compagnie des Messageries Aériennes, established in 1919 by Louis-Charles Breguet, offering a mail and freight service between Le Bourget Airport, Paris and Lesquin Airport, Lille.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The first German airline to use heavier than air aircraft was Deutsche Luft-Reederei (DLR) established in 1917 which started operating in February 1919.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In its first year, the DLR operated regularly scheduled flights on routes with a combined length of nearly 1000 miles.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] By 1921 the DLR network was more than 3000 km (1865 miles) long, and included destinations in the Netherlands, Scandinavia and the Baltic Republics.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Another important German airline was Junkers Luftverkehr, which began operations in 1921.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It was a division of the aircraft manufacturer Junkers, which became a separate company in 1924.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It operated joint-venture airlines in Austria, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Hungary, Latvia, Norway, Poland, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Dutch airline KLM made its first flight in 1920, and is the oldest airline still using the original name.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Established by aviator Albert Plesman, it was immediately awarded a "Royal" predicate from Queen Wilhelmina.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Its first flight was from Croydon Airport, London to Amsterdam, using a leased DH-16 from Aircraft Transport and Travel, carrying two British journalists and a number of newspapers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1921, KLM started scheduled services.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In Finland, the charter establishing Aero O/Y (now Finnair) was signed in the city of Helsinki on 12 September 1923.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Junkers F.13 D-335 became the first aircraft of the company, when Aero took delivery of it on 14 March 1924.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The first flight was between Helsinki and Tallinn, capital of Estonia, and it took place on 20 March 1924, one week later.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In the Soviet Union, the Chief Administration of the Civil Air Fleet was established in 1921.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] One of its first acts was to help found Deutsch-Russische Luftverkehrs A.G.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] (Deruluft), a German-Russian joint venture to provide air transport from Russia to the West.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Domestic air service began around the same time, when Dobrolyot started operations on 15 July 1923 between Moscow and Nizhni Novgorod.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Since 1932 all operations had been carried under the name Aeroflot.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Early European airlines tended to favor comfort – the passenger cabins were often spacious with luxurious interiors – over speed and efficiency.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The relatively basic navigational capabilities of pilots at the time also meant that delays due to the weather were commonplace.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] By the early 1920s, small airlines were struggling to compete, and there was a movement towards increased rationalization and consolidation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1924, Imperial Airways was formed from the merger of Instone Air Line Company, British Marine Air Navigation, Daimler Airway and Handley Page Transport, to allow British airlines to compete with stiff competition from French and German airlines that were enjoying heavy government subsidies.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The airline was a pioneer in surveying and opening up air routes across the world to serve far-flung parts of the British Empire and to enhance trade and integration.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The first new airliner ordered by Imperial Airways, was the Handley Page W8f *City of Washington*, delivered on 3 November 1924.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In the first year of operation the company carried 11,395 passengers and 212,380 letters.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In April 1925, the film *The Lost World* became the first film to be screened for passengers on a scheduled airliner flight when it was shown on the London-Paris route.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Two French airlines also merged to form Air Union on 1 January 1923.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] This later merged with four other French airlines to become Air France, the country's flagship carrier to this day, on 17 May 1933.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Germany's Deutsche Lufthansa was created in 1926 by merger of two airlines, one of them Junkers Luftverkehr.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Lufthansa, due to the Junkers heritage and unlike most other airlines at the time, became a major investor in airlines outside of Europe, providing capital to Varig and Avianca.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] German airliners built by Junkers, Dornier, and Fokker were among the most advanced in the world at the time.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1926, Alan Cobham surveyed a flight route from the UK to Cape Town, South Africa, following this up with another proving flight to Melbourne, Australia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Other routes to British India and the Far East were also charted and demonstrated at this time.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Regular services to Cairo and Basra began in 1927 and were extended to Karachi in 1929.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The London-Australia service was inaugurated in 1932 with the Handley Page HP 42 airliners.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Further services were opened up to Calcutta, Rangoon, Singapore, Brisbane and Hong Kong passengers departed London on 14 March 1936 following the establishment of a branch from Penang to Hong Kong.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] France began an air mail service to Morocco in 1919 that was bought out in 1927, renamed Aéropostale, and injected with capital to become a major international carrier.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1933, Aéropostale went bankrupt, was nationalized and merged into Air France.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Although Germany lacked colonies, it also began expanding its services globally.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1931, the airship Graf Zeppelin began offering regular scheduled passenger service between Germany and South America, usually every two weeks, which continued until 1937.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1936, the airship Hindenburg entered passenger service and successfully crossed the Atlantic 36 times before crashing at Lakehurst, New Jersey, on 6 May 1937.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1938, a weekly air service from Berlin to Kabul, Afghanistan, started operating.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] From February 1934 until World War II began in 1939, Deutsche Lufthansa operated an airmail service from Stuttgart, Germany via Spain, the Canary Islands and West Africa to Natal in Brazil.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] This was the first time an airline flew across an ocean.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] By the end of the 1930s Aeroflot had become the world's largest airline, employing more than 4,000 pilots and 60,000 other service personnel and operating around 3,000 aircraft (of which 75% were considered obsolete by its own standards).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] During the Soviet era Aeroflot was synonymous with Russian civil aviation, as it was the only air carrier.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It became the first airline in the world to operate sustained regular jet services on 15 September 1956 with the Tupolev Tu-104.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Deregulation of the European Union airspace in the early 1990s has had substantial effect on the structure of the industry there.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The shift towards 'budget' airlines on shorter routes has been significant.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Airlines such as EasyJet and Ryanair have often grown at the expense of the traditional national airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] There has also been a trend for these national airlines themselves to be privatized such as has occurred for Aer Lingus and British Airways.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Other national airlines, including Italy's Alitalia, suffered – particularly with the rapid increase of oil prices in early 2008.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Tony Jannus conducted the United States' first scheduled commercial airline flight on January 1, 1914, for the St.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The 23-minute flight traveled between St.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Petersburg, Florida and Tampa, Florida, passing some 50 feet (15 m) above Tampa Bay in Jannus' Benoist XIV wood and muslin biplane flying boat.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Petersburg, who paid $400 for the privilege of sitting on a wooden bench in the open cockpit.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Airboat line operated for about four months, carrying more than 1,200 passengers who paid $5 each.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Chalk's International Airlines claimed to have begun a service between Miami and Bimini in the Bahamas in February 1919.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Lauderdale, Chalk's claimed to be the oldest continuously operating airline in the United States until its closure in 2008.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Following World War I, the United States found itself swamped with aviators.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Many decided to take their war-surplus aircraft on barnstorming campaigns, performing aerobatic maneuvers to woo crowds.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1918, the United States Post Office Department won the financial backing of Congress to begin experimenting with air mail service, initially using Curtiss Jenny aircraft that had been procured by the United States Army Air Service.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Private operators were the first to fly the mail but due to numerous accidents the US Army was tasked with mail delivery.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] During the Army's involvement they proved to be too unreliable and lost their air mail duties.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] By the mid-1920s, the Post Office had developed its own air mail network, based on a transcontinental backbone between New York City and San Francisco.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] To supplement this service, they offered twelve contracts for spur routes to independent bidders.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Some of the carriers that won these routes would, through time and mergers, evolve into Pan Am, Delta Air Lines, Braniff Airways, American Airlines, United Airlines (originally a division of Boeing), Trans World Airlines, Northwest Airlines, and Eastern Air Lines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Service during the early 1920s was sporadic: most airlines at the time were focused on carrying bags of mail.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1925, however, the Ford Motor Company bought out the Stout Aircraft Company and began construction of the all-metal Ford Trimotor, which became the first successful American airliner.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] With a 12-passenger capacity, the Trimotor made passenger service potentially profitable.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Air service was seen as a supplement to rail service in the American transportation network.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] At the same time, Juan Trippe began a crusade to create an air network that would link America to the world, and he achieved this goal through his airline, Pan Am, with a fleet of flying boats that linked Los Angeles to Shanghai and Boston to London.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Pan Am and Northwest Airways (which began flights to Canada in the 1920s) were the only U.S. airlines to go international before the 1940s.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] With the introduction of the Boeing 247 and Douglas DC-3 in the 1930s, the U.S. airline industry was generally profitable, even during the Great Depression.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] This trend continued until the beginning of World War II.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] World War II, like World War I, brought new life to the airline industry.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Many airlines in the Allied countries were flush from lease contracts to the military, and foresaw a future explosive demand for civil air transport, for both passengers and cargo.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] They were eager to invest in the newly emerging flagships of air travel such as the Boeing Stratocruiser, Lockheed Constellation, and Douglas DC-6.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Most of these new aircraft were based on American bombers such as the B-29, which had spearheaded research into new technologies such as pressurization.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Most offered increased efficiency from both added speed and greater payload.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Vickers Viscount and Lockheed L-188 Electra inaugurated turboprop transport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] On 4 October 1958, British Overseas Airways Corporation started transatlantic flights between London Heathrow and New York Idlewild with a Comet 4, and Pan Am followed on 26 October with a Boeing 707 service between New York and Paris.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The next big boost for the airlines would come in the 1970s, when the Boeing 747, McDonnell Douglas DC-10, and Lockheed L-1011 inaugurated widebody ("jumbo jet") service, which is still the standard in international travel.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Tupolev Tu-144 and its Western counterpart, Concorde, made supersonic travel a reality.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Concorde first flew in 1969 and operated through 2003.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In 1972, Airbus began producing Europe's most commercially successful line of airliners to date.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The added efficiencies for these aircraft were often not in speed, but in passenger capacity, payload, and range.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Airbus also features modern electronic cockpits that were common across their aircraft to enable pilots to fly multiple models with minimal cross-training.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The 1978 U.S. airline industry deregulation lowered federally controlled barriers for new airlines just as a downturn in the nation's economy occurred.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] New start-ups entered during the downturn, during which time they found aircraft and funding, contracted hangar and maintenance services, trained new employees, and recruited laid-off staff from other airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Major airlines dominated their routes through aggressive pricing and additional capacity offerings, often swamping new start-ups.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In the place of high barriers to entry imposed by regulation, the major airlines implemented an equally high barrier called loss leader pricing.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In this strategy an already established and dominant airline stomps out its competition by lowering airfares on specific routes, below the cost of operating on it, choking out any chance a start-up airline may have.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The industry side effect is an overall drop in revenue and service quality.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Since deregulation in 1978 the average domestic ticket price has dropped by 40%.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] After incurring massive losses, the airlines of the USA relied upon Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings to continue doing business.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] America West Airlines (which has since merged with US Airways) remained a significant survivor from this new entrant era, as dozens, even hundreds, have gone under.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In many ways, the biggest winner in the deregulated environment was the air passenger.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Although not exclusively attributable to deregulation, indeed the U.S. witnessed an explosive growth in demand for air travel.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Many millions who had never or rarely flown before became regular fliers, even joining frequent flyer loyalty programs and receiving free flights and other benefits from their flying.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] New services and higher frequencies meant that business fliers could fly to another city, do business, and return the same day, from almost any point in the country.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Air travel's advantages put long-distance intercity railroad travel and bus lines under pressure, with most of the latter having withered away, whilst the former is still protected under nationalization through the continuing existence of Amtrak.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] By the 1980s, almost half of the total flying in the world took place in the U.S., and today the domestic industry operates over 10,000 daily departures nationwide.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Toward the end of the century, a new style of low cost airline emerged, offering a no-frills product at a lower price.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Southwest Airlines, JetBlue, AirTran Airways, Skybus Airlines and other low-cost carriers began to represent a serious challenge to the so-called "legacy airlines", as did their low-cost counterparts in many other countries.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Their commercial viability represented a serious competitive threat to the legacy carriers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] However, of these, ATA and Skybus have since ceased operations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Increasingly since 1978, US airlines have been reincorporated and spun off by newly created and internally led management companies, and thus becoming nothing more than operating units and subsidiaries with limited financially decisive control.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Among some of these holding companies and parent companies which are relatively well known, are the UAL Corporation, along with the AMR Corporation, among a long list of airline holding companies sometime recognized worldwide.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Thus the last 50 years of the airline industry have varied from reasonably profitable, to devastatingly depressed.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] As the first major market to deregulate the industry in 1978, U.S. airlines have experienced more turbulence than almost any other country or region.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In fact, no U.S. legacy carrier survived bankruptcy-free.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Congress passed the Air Transportation Safety and System Stabilization Act (P.L.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] 107–42) in response to a severe liquidity crisis facing the already-troubled airline industry in the aftermath of the September 11 attacks.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Through the ATSB Congress sought to provide cash infusions to carriers for both the cost of the four-day federal shutdown of the airlines and the incremental losses incurred through December 31, 2001, as a result of the terrorist attacks.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] This resulted in the first government bailout of the 21st century.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Between 2000 and 2005 US airlines lost $30 billion with wage cuts of over $15 billion and 100,000 employees laid off.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In recognition of the essential national economic role of a healthy aviation system, Congress authorized partial compensation of up to $5 billion in cash subject to review by the U.S.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Department of Transportation and up to $10 billion in loan guarantees subject to review by a newly created Air Transportation Stabilization Board (ATSB).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The applications to DOT for reimbursements were subjected to rigorous multi-year reviews not only by DOT program personnel but also by the Government Accountability Office and the DOT Inspector General.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Ultimately, the federal government provided $4.6 billion in one-time, subject-to-income-tax cash payments to 427 U.S. air carriers, with no provision for repayment, essentially a gift from the taxpayers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] (Passenger carriers operating scheduled service received approximately $4 billion, subject to tax.) In addition, the ATSB approved loan guarantees to six airlines totaling approximately $1.6 billion.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Treasury Department show that the government recouped the $1.6 billion and a profit of $339 million from the fees, interest and purchase of discounted airline stock associated with loan guarantees.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] As of May 2018 the four largest major carriers controlled 70% of the U.S. passenger market.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Although Philippine Airlines (PAL) was officially founded on February 26, 1941, its license to operate as an airliner was derived from merged Philippine Aerial Taxi Company (PATCO) established by mining magnate Emmanuel N.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Bachrach on 3 December 1930, making it Asia's oldest scheduled carrier still in operation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Commercial air service commenced three weeks later from Manila to Baguio, making it Asia's first airline route.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Bachrach's death in 1937 paved the way for its eventual merger with Philippine Airlines in March 1941 and made it Asia's oldest airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It is also the oldest airline in Asia still operating under its current name.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Bachrach's majority share in PATCO was bought by beer magnate Andres R.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Soriano in 1939 upon the advice of General Douglas MacArthur and later merged with newly formed Philippine Airlines with PAL as the surviving entity.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Soriano has controlling interest in both airlines before the merger.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] PAL restarted service on 15 March 1941, with a single Beech Model 18 NPC-54 aircraft, which started its daily services between Manila (from Nielson Field) and Baguio, later to expand with larger aircraft such as the DC-3 and Vickers Viscount.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In Japan, Japan Air Transport was established in 1928 as the national flag carrier.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Upon the completion of Haneda Airport in 1931, it became the airline's hub.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The airline initially operated domestic routes such as Tokyo–Osaka and Osaka–Fukuoka.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In September 1929, it opened its first overseas route, which connected Fukuoka to Dalian in the Kwantung Leased Territory via Seoul and Pyongyang in Japanese Korea.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] After Japan established the puppet state of Manchukuo, the airline opened routes to major cities within this territory.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The company was reorganized as Japan Airways in 1938.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] During the Second World War, it operated routes to various Japanese-occupied territories and Thailand.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The company was dissolved immediately after the war, as civil aviation was prohibited by the Allied Occupation Forces.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Civil aviation in Japan did not resume until the founding of Japan Airlines in 1951.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Cathay Pacific was one of the first airlines to be launched among the other Asian countries in 1946.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The license to operate as an airliner was granted by the federal government body after reviewing the necessity at the national assembly.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Hanjin occupies the largest ownership of Korean Air as well as few low-budget airlines as of now.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Korean Air is one of the four founders of SkyTeam, which was established in 2000.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Asiana Airlines, launched in 1988, joined Star Alliance in 2003.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] India was also one of the first countries to embrace civil aviation.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] One of the first Asian airline companies was Air India, which was founded as Tata Airlines in 1932, a division of Tata Sons Ltd.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The airline was founded by India's leading industrialist, JRD Tata.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Tata himself flew a single engined De Havilland Puss Moth carrying air mail (postal mail of Imperial Airways) from Karachi to Bombay via Ahmedabad.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The aircraft continued to Madras via Bellary piloted by Royal Air Force pilot Nevill Vintcent.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Tata Airlines was also one of the world's first major airlines which began its operations without any support from the Government.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] With the outbreak of World War II, the airline presence in Asia came to a relative halt, with many new flag carriers donating their aircraft for military aid and other uses.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Following the end of the war in 1945, regular commercial service was restored in India and Tata Airlines became a public limited company on 29 July 1946, under the name Air India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] After the independence of India, 49% of the airline was acquired by the Government of India.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In return, the airline was granted status to operate international services from India as the designated flag carrier under the name Air India International.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] On 31 July 1946, a chartered Philippine Airlines (PAL) DC-4 ferried 40 American servicemen to Oakland, California, from Nielson Airport in Makati with stops in Guam, Wake Island, Johnston Atoll and Honolulu, Hawaii, making PAL the first Asian airline to cross the Pacific Ocean.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] A regular service between Manila and San Francisco was started in December.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] It was during this year that the airline was designated as the flag carrier of Philippines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] During the era of decolonization, newly born Asian countries started to embrace air transport.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] All the previous airlines started regular operations well before World War II.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Puerto Rican commercial airlines such as Prinair, Oceanair, Fina Air and Vieques Air Link came much after the second world war, as did several others from other countries like Mexico's Interjet and Volaris, Venezuela's Aserca Airlines and others.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The air travel market has evolved rapidly over recent years in Latin America.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Some industry estimates indicated in 2011 that over 2,000 new aircraft will begin service over the next five years in this region.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] These airlines serve domestic flights within their countries, as well as connections within Latin America and also overseas flights to North America, Europe, Australia, and Asia.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Only four airline groups – Avianca, Panama's Copa, Mexico's Volaris, and LATAM Airlines – have international subsidiaries and cover many destinations within the Americas as well as major hubs in other continents.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] LATAM with Chile as the central operation along with Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, Brazil and Argentina and formerly with some operations in the Dominican Republic.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The Avianca group has its main operation in Colombia based around the hub in Bogotá, Colombia, as well as subsidiaries in various Latin American countries with hubs in San Salvador, El Salvador, as well as Lima, Peru, with a smaller operation in Ecuador.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Copa has subsidiaries Copa Airlines Colombia and Wingo, both in Colombia, while Volaris of Mexico has Volaris Costa Rica and Volaris El Salvador, and the Irelandia group formerly included Viva Aerobus of Mexico, Viva Colombia and Viva Air Peru.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Many countries have national airlines that the government owns and operates.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Fully private airlines are subject to much government regulation for economic, political, and safety concerns.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] For instance, governments often intervene to halt airline labor actions to protect the free flow of people, communications, and goods between different regions without compromising safety.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The United States, Australia, and to a lesser extent Brazil, Mexico, India, the United Kingdom, and Japan have "deregulated" their airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In the past, these governments dictated airfares, route networks, and other operational requirements for each airline.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Since deregulation, airlines have been largely free to negotiate their own operating arrangements with different airports, enter and exit routes easily, and to levy airfares and supply flights according to market demand.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The entry barriers for new airlines are lower in a deregulated market, and so the U.S. has seen hundreds of airlines start up (sometimes for only a brief operating period).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] This has produced far greater competition than before deregulation in most markets.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The added competition, together with pricing freedom, means that new entrants often take market share with highly reduced rates that, to a limited degree, full service airlines must match.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] This is a major constraint on profitability for established carriers, which tend to have a higher cost base.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] As a result, profitability in a deregulated market is uneven for most airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] These forces have caused some major airlines to go out of business, in addition to most of the poorly established new entrants.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In the United States, the airline industry is dominated by four large firms.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Because of industry consolidation, after fuel prices dropped considerably in 2015, very little of the savings were passed on to consumers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Groups such as the International Civil Aviation Organization establish worldwide standards for safety and other vital concerns.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Most international air traffic is regulated by bilateral agreements between countries, which designate specific carriers to operate on specific routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] The model of such an agreement was the Bermuda Agreement between the US and UK following World War II, which designated airports to be used for transatlantic flights and gave each government the authority to nominate carriers to operate routes.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Bilateral agreements are based on the "freedoms of the air", a group of generalized traffic rights ranging from the freedom to overfly a country to the freedom to provide domestic flights within a country (a very rarely granted right known as cabotage).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Most agreements permit airlines to fly from their home country to designated airports in the other country: some also extend the freedom to provide continuing service to a third country, or to another destination in the other country while carrying passengers from overseas.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] In the 1990s, "open skies" agreements became more common.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] These agreements take many of these regulatory powers from state governments and open up international routes to further competition.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p01] Open skies agreements have met some criticism, particularly within the European Union, whose airlines would be at a comparative disadvantage with the United States' because of cabotage restrictions.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] In 2017, 4.1 billion passengers have been carried by airlines in 41.9 million commercial scheduled flights (an average payload of 98 passengers), for 7.75 trillion passenger kilometers (an average trip of 1890 km) over 45,091 airline routes served globally.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] In 2016, air transport generated $704.4 billion of revenue in 2016, employed 10.2 million workers, supported 65.5 million jobs and $2.7 trillion of economic activity: 3.6% of the global GDP.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] In July 2016, the total weekly airline capacity was 181.1 billion Available Seat Kilometers (+6.9% compared to July 2015): 57.6bn in Asia-Pacific, 47.7bn in Europe, 46.2bn in North America, 12.2bn in Middle East, 12.0bn in Latin America and 5.4bn in Africa.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Thus all but a small percentage of the income from ticket sales is paid out to a wide variety of external providers or internal cost centers.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Moreover, the industry is structured so that airlines often act as tax collectors.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Airline fuel is untaxed because of a series of treaties existing between countries.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Ticket prices include a number of fees, taxes and surcharges beyond the control of airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Airlines are also responsible for enforcing government regulations.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] If airlines carry passengers without proper documentation on an international flight, they are responsible for returning them back to the original country.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Analysis of the 1992–1996 period shows that every player in the air transport chain is far more profitable than the airlines, who collect and pass through fees and revenues to them from ticket sales.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] While airlines as a whole earned 6% return on capital employed (2–3.5% less than the cost of capital), airports earned 10%, catering companies 10–13%, handling companies 11–14%, aircraft lessors 15%, aircraft manufacturers 16%, and global distribution companies more than 30%.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] There has been continuing cost competition from low cost airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Many companies emulate Southwest Airlines in various respects.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] The lines between full-service and low-cost airlines have become blurred – e.g., with most "full service" airlines introducing baggage check fees despite Southwest not doing so.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Many airlines in the U.S. and elsewhere have experienced business difficulty.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] U.S. airlines that have declared Chapter 11 bankruptcy since 1990 have included American Airlines, Continental Airlines (twice), Delta Air Lines, Northwest Airlines, Pan Am, United Airlines and US Airways (twice).
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Where an airline has established an engineering base at an airport, then there may be considerable economic advantages in using that same airport as a preferred focus (or "hub") for its scheduled flights.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Fuel hedging is a contractual tool used by transportation companies like airlines to reduce their exposure to volatile and potentially rising fuel costs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Several low-cost carriers such as Southwest Airlines adopt this practice.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Southwest is credited with maintaining strong business profits between 1999 and the early 2000s due to its fuel hedging policy.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Many other airlines are replicating Southwest's hedging policy to control their fuel costs.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] An average US major Boeing 757-200 flies 1,252 miles (2,015 km) stages 11.3 block hours per day and costs $2,550 per block hour: $923 of ownership, $590 of maintenance, $548 of fuel and $489 of crew; or $13.34 per 186 seats per block hour.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] For a Boeing 737-500, a low-cost carrier like Southwest have lower operating costs at $1,526 than a full service one like United at $2,974, and higher productivity with 399,746 ASM per day against 264,284, resulting in a unit cost of 0.38 $cts/ASM against 1.13 $cts/ASM.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] McKinsey observes that "newer technology, larger aircraft, and increasingly efficient operations continually drive down the cost of running an airline", from nearly 40 US cents per ASK at the beginning of the jet age, to just above 10 cents since 2000.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Those improvements were passed onto the customer due to high competition: fares have been falling throughout the history of airlines.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Airlines assign prices to their services in an attempt to maximize profitability.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] The pricing of airline tickets has become increasingly complicated over the years and is now largely determined by computerized yield management systems.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Because of the complications in scheduling flights and maintaining profitability, airlines have many loopholes that can be used by the knowledgeable traveler.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Many of these airfare secrets are becoming more and more known to the general public, so airlines are forced to make constant adjustments.
[src:empower-aircraft-power-adapter/airlines-p02] Most airlines use differentiated pricing, a form of price discrimination, to sell air services at varying prices simultaneously to different segments.
